"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[446],{4446:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"$":[{"id":1,"slug":"cybersecurity","title":"Cybersecurity","content":"### Why Cybersecurity?\\nI’ve always been drawn to understanding how systems break — and how to protect them. Cybersecurity combines technology, psychology, and strategy — it’s not just about defending systems, but about understanding how attackers think. \\n\\n I became deeply interested in cybersecurity after joining Toyota Canada’s Information Security team, where I worked on everything from risk assessments to security awareness. \\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD10 My Experience with Cybersecurity\\n Here’s where I’ve built hands-on cybersecurity knowledge and skills: \\n\\n- Toyota Canada Inc. (Information Security Intern) (2024)\\n- [[CompTIA Security+]] (2025)\\n- [[Google Cybersecurity Certification]] (2024) \\n- Qualys Vulnerability Management Certification (2024)\\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDED What I’m Focusing on Next \\n- Cloud Security (AWS & GCP) \\n- Scripting for Security (Python, PowerShell) \\n- Penetration Testing Methodologies\\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDF0 Tools I’ve Used \\n- Qualys VM \\n- IBM QRadar(SIEM) \\n- CrowdStrike EDR\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCDA Certifications & Learning Resources \\n**Certifications:**\\n- [[CompTIA Security+]] \\n- [[Google Cybersecurity Certification]] \\n- Qualys Vulnerability Management Certification\\n**Learning Resources** \\n- [MITRE ATT&CK Framework](https://attack.mitre.org/) \\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/) \\n- [TryHackMe](https://tryhackme.com/) \\n- [Hack The Box](https://www.hackthebox.com/) \\n- [NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF)](https://www.nist.gov/cyberframework) \\n- [PortSwigger Web Security Academy](https://portswigger.net/web-security) \\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCA1 How to Get Started in Cybersecurity\\n Here’s what worked for me:\\n 1. **Start with fundamentals.** Get cybersecurity-related certification (free certification (ex: [[Google Cybersecurity Certification]]), [[CompTIA Security+]]), it will give you a solid foundation.\\n 2. **Learn by doing.** [TryHackMe](https://tryhackme.com/) and [Hack The Box](https://www.hackthebox.com/) are amazing for hands-on practice. \\n 3. **Work on projects.** Analyze sample incidents, write scripts to automate security tasks, or document mock risk assessments. \\n 4. **Intern or volunteer.** Working on real projects (like I did at Toyota) gives perspective that labs can’t.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCA1 \uD83D\uDE80 Final Thoughts\\n  Security isn’t about achieving perfection — it’s about staying ahead.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2024-01-14","created":"2024-01-14T10:00:00Z","updated":"2024-01-14T10:00:00Z"},{"id":2,"slug":"comptia-security-plus","title":"CompTIA Security+","content":"### \uD83D\uDEE1️ CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)\\n#### \uD83D\uDCC5 Exam Date: September 7, 2025\\n#### ⏳ Study Duration: About 1.5 months\\n#### \uD83D\uDCC4 Study Notes\\n[Download Security+ Study Notes PDF](/pdf/CompTIA Security+.pdf)\\n\\n### ⭐ Why I Pursued Security+\\nCompTIA Security+ was my first step into building a strong cybersecurity foundation. I used it to learn core security concepts, and strengthen my knowledge for future internships.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCD8 Key Domains & Important Topics\\n Below are the most valuable Security+ topics. Many link to deeper notes. \\n#### \uD83D\uDD10 Domain 1 — General Security Concepts\\n- [[CIA Triad]] \\n- [[Security Controls]] \\n- [[Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting (AAA)]] \\n- [[Zero Trust Model]] \\n- [[PKI & Encryption]] \\n#### \uD83E\uDDEA Domain 2 — Threats, Vulnerabilities & Mitigations \\n- [[Common Threat Actors]] \\n- [[Social Engineering]] \\n- [[Malware Types]] \\n- [[Vulnerability Types]] \\n#### \uD83C\uDF10 Domain 3 — Security Architecture \\n- [[Defense in Depth]] \\n- [[Secure Network Segmentation]] \\n- [[Data Protection]] \\n#### \uD83D\uDDA5️ Domain 4 — Security Operations \\n- [[Secure Baselines & Hardening]] \\n- [[Vulnerability Management Lifecycle]] \\n- [[Identity and Access Management (IAM)]] \\n- [[Incident Response Process]]\\n#### ⚙️ Domain 5 — Security Program Management and Oversight \\n- [[Security Policies]] \\n- [[Risk Management]] \\n- [[Audits & Assessments]] \\n- [[Security Awareness Training]] \\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDF0 Resources\\n#### \uD83C\uDFA5 Video Courses\\n- Jason Dion – CompTIA Security+ Full Course (Udemy)\\n- CyberCraft – Security+ PBQ Playlist (YouTube)\\n- Cyber James – Security+ Practice Test Videos (YouTube)\\n#### \uD83D\uDCD8 Practice Exams\\n- Jason Dion – Practice Exam Sets (Udemy)\\n- ExamCompass Security+ Practice Tests\\n- TechExam.pro – Security+ Full Practice Exams \\n### \uD83D\uDEE3️ My Personal Tips  \\n 1. **Understand concepts, don’t memorize answers.** \\n 2. **Do 500–700 practice questions minimum.** \\n 3. **Use multiple sources, not one.**","tags":["Cybersecurity","Certification"],"date":"2025-07-26","created":"2025-07-26T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-07-26T10:00:00Z"},{"id":3,"slug":"risk-management","title":"Risk Management","content":"Risk management involves identifying, analyzing, responding to, and monitoring risks that could impact an organization\'s operations or objectives.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD0D Risk Identification\\nFinding potential risks through: \\n- Brainstorming\\n- Checklists\\n- Interviews\\n- Scenario analysis\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCCA Risk Assessment\\nTypes:\\n- **Ad Hoc:** Done when needed.\\n- **Recurring:** Regularly scheduled (e.g., yearly).\\n- **One-Time:** For unique projects.\\n- **Continuous:** Ongoing monitoring.\\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDEE Risk Analysis\\n**Qualitative:** Subjective, high-level evaluation (likelihood + impact).\\n\\n**Quantitative:** Numerical evaluation using metrics:\\n\\n- **SLE:** Expected loss per event.\\n- **ARO:** Estimated frequency per year.\\n- **ALE:** Annual expected loss (SLE \xd7 ARO).\\n- **Exposure Factor:** Percentage of asset lost.\\n- **Impact:** Effect on financial, operational, or reputational areas.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCD8 Risk Register (What It Tracks)\\n- Description of the risk\\n- Impact & likelihood\\n- Cost implications\\n- Risk owner\\n- Key Risk Indicators (KRIs)\\n\\n### \uD83C\uDFAF Risk Appetite & Tolerance\\n- **Risk Appetite:** Amount of risk an organization is willing to accept.\\n- **Risk Tolerance:** Acceptable variance around the appetite.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDEE0️ Risk Treatment Strategies\\n- **Mitigate:** Reduce likelihood or impact.\\n- **Accept:** Acknowledge and handle if it occurs.\\n- **Avoid:** Change plans to eliminate it.\\n- **Transfer:** Shift risk to another party (e.g., insurance).\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD0E Risk Monitoring\\nOngoing tracking of risks and effectiveness of responses.\\n- **Residual Risk:** Risk remaining after actions.\\n- **Control Risk:** When controls weaken or become less effective.\\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDE9 Business Impact Concepts\\n- **RTO:** Maximum acceptable downtime.\\n- **RPO:** Maximum acceptable data loss.\\n- **MTTR:** Time needed to repair a failure.\\n- **MTBF:** Average time between failures.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-15","created":"2025-08-15T09:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-15T09:00:00Z"},{"id":4,"slug":"security-policies","title":"Security Policies","content":"Security policies are foundational documents that define an organization\'s approach to protecting information, systems, and operations. They establish rules, procedures, and responsibilities for maintaining security.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCDD Policy Types & Purpose\\n**Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)**\\n- Defines do\'s and don\'ts for users interacting with IT systems\\n- Outlines proper use of company resources and equipment\\n**Information Security Policy**\\n- Outlines how organizations protect information assets\\n- Addresses threats from both internal and external sources\\n**Business Continuity Plan**\\n- Focuses on continuing critical operations during disruptions\\n- Ensures essential business functions remain operational\\n**Disaster Recovery Plan**\\n- Specifically recovers IT systems and data after disasters\\n- Works alongside business continuity efforts\\n**Incident Response Plan**\\n- Provides structured approach for handling security incidents\\n- Defines roles and procedures for incident containment\\n**Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC)**\\n- Guides secure software development within organization\\n- Integrates security throughout development phases\\n**Change Management Policy**\\n- Ensures changes are implemented in controlled manner\\n- Minimizes risk of disruptions from system modifications\\n\\n### \uD83C\uDFAF Key Objectives\\n- Establish clear security expectations\\n- Ensure regulatory compliance\\n- Protect organizational assets\\n- Minimize business disruptions\\n- Provide framework for consistent operations","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-16","created":"2025-08-16T11:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-16T11:00:00Z"},{"id":5,"slug":"audits-and-assessments","title":"Audits & Assessments","content":"## \uD83D\uDCDD Audits & Assessments \\nAudits and assessments evaluate how secure, compliant, and trustworthy an organization\'s systems and processes are. They play a major role in [[Risk Management]] and penetration testing.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD10 Attestation\\nFormal validation proving accuracy, authenticity, or integrity.\\n- **Software Attestation:** Ensures software hasn\'t been altered.\\n- **Hardware Attestation:** Confirms hardware integrity.\\n- **System Attestation:** Verifies overall system security posture.\\n- **Pen Test Attestation Letter:** Proof that a penetration test was performed.\\n\\n## \uD83C\uDFE2 Internal Audits & Assessments\\nUsed to evaluate internal controls, compliance, and system integrity.\\n- **Internal Audit:** Systematic review of internal processes.\\n- **Compliance Checks:** Ensure adherence to laws, standards, and policies.\\n- **Internal Assessments & Self-Assessments:** Identify internal risks and vulnerabilities.\\n- **Audit Committee:** Oversees internal audit activities.\\n- **Cybersecurity Self-Assessment:** Baseline evaluation of cyber maturity (e.g., MCIT checklist).\\n\\n## \uD83C\uDF10 External Audits & Assessments\\nPerformed by third-party or regulatory bodies.\\n- **External Audit:** Independent validation of controls (GDPR, HIPAA, PCI DSS).\\n- **External Assessments:** In-depth vulnerability and risk reviews.\\n- **Independent Third-Party Audit:** Builds trust with customers and regulators.\\n- **Regulatory Compliance Exams:** Formal inspections of security posture.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDEE0️ Penetration Testing\\nSimulated cyberattacks to uncover vulnerabilities.\\n- **Physical Pen Testing:** Tests locks, badges, and physical access.\\n- **Red Teaming:** Offensive testing simulating real attackers.\\n- **Blue Teaming:** Defensive monitoring & incident response.\\n- **Purple Teaming:** Collaboration between red and blue for improvement.\\n\\n### Knowledge Levels\\n- **Known Environment:** Full information provided.\\n- **Partially Known:** Limited info.\\n- **Unknown (Black Box):** No prior knowledge.\\n\\n### Reconnaissance\\n- **Passive:** No interaction, low detection.\\n- **Active:** Direct probing, more info but higher risk.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDE80 Metasploit Framework (Pen Test Tool)\\nCommon tool used during penetration testing.\\n- **Auxiliary:** Scanners, sniffers, fuzzers.\\n- **Post:** Actions after exploiting a system.\\n- **Payloads:** Execute code for access/control.\\n- **Encoders:** Evade IDS/IPS by encoding payloads.\\n- **Nops:** Maintain payload structure.\\n- **Evasion:** Techniques to bypass defenses.\\n\\n### Basic Commands\\n```\\nmsfconsole          # Launches the Metasploit framework\\nsearch [term]       # Searches for modules\\nuse [module_path]   # Selects a module to use\\nset rhosts [IP]     # Sets the target host IP\\nset lhost [IP]      # Sets the local listener IP (reverse shells)\\nshow payloads       # Shows compatible payloads\\nrun                 # Executes the module\\nsessions -l         # Lists active sessions\\nsessions [id]       # Interacts with a specific session\\n```\\n\\nMetasploit helps testers discover exploitable weaknesses and validate real-world attack paths.\\n","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-17","created":"2025-08-17T14:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-17T14:00:00Z"},{"id":6,"slug":"authentication-authorization-accounting-aaa","title":"Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting (AAA)","content":"## \uD83D\uDEE1️ Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting (AAA)\\nAAA is a core framework for securing systems by verifying identity, controlling access, and tracking activity.\\n\\n### Authentication\\nVerifying the identity of users or systems.\\n- **Knowledge Factor:** Passwords, PINs.\\n- **Possession Factor:** Tokens, smart cards.\\n- **Inherence Factor:** Biometrics (fingerprint, facial recognition).\\n- **Action Factor:** Unique user actions.\\n- **Location Factor:** Grant access based on geographic location.\\n- **2FA/MFA:** Multiple verification methods.\\n- **System Authentication:** Certificates, SSH keys, API tokens.\\n\\n### Authorization\\nDefines what authenticated users can access.\\n- **Models:** RBAC, ABAC, DAC, MAC.\\n- Ensures proper permissions and protects sensitive data.\\n\\n### Accounting\\nTracks user activities and resource usage for auditing and compliance.\\n- **Audit Trail:** Chronological records of user actions.\\n- **Technologies:** Syslog servers, SIEMs, network analysis tools (e.g., Wireshark).\\n- Supports forensic analysis, compliance, resource optimization, and accountability.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-01","created":"2025-08-01T16:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-01T16:00:00Z"},{"id":7,"slug":"security-awareness-training","title":"Security Awareness Training","content":"## \uD83D\uDD10 Security Awareness Training\\nSecurity awareness helps employees recognize threats, reduce risky behavior, and protect organizational data.\\n\\n### \uD83C\uDFA3 Phishing Awareness\\n- Beware of urgency, unusual requests, mismatched URLs, and poor grammar.\\n- Always verify sender addresses.\\n- Report suspicious messages to the security team.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDC64 Anomalous & Risky Behavior\\n- **Risky:** Installing unauthorized software, clicking unknown links.\\n- **Unexpected:** Logins from unusual times/locations.\\n- **Unintentional:** Sending data to the wrong recipient.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDEE1️ User Guidance\\n- Follow company policies and handbooks.\\n- Maintain situational awareness (e.g., shoulder surfing, tailgating).\\n- Use password managers to store credentials securely.\\n\\n### ☢️ Insider Threat Basics\\nThreats can come from internal users due to negligence or malicious intent.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCBE Removable Media Safety\\nNever plug in unknown USB drives — may contain malware.\\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDE0 Social Engineering Cues\\nAttackers exploit:\\n- **Authority**\\n- **Urgency**\\n- **Social Proof**\\n- **Scarcity**\\n- **Likability**\\n- **Fear**\\n\\n### \uD83C\uDF0D Remote & Hybrid Work\\n- Use VPNs and MFA.\\n- Keep company devices updated.\\n- Use secure collaboration tools.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCCA Reporting & Training Cycle\\n- **Initial:** Onboarding security training.\\n- **Recurring:** Periodic refreshers.\\n- **Execution:** Campaigns, simulations, and continuous monitoring.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-16","created":"2025-08-16T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-16T10:00:00Z"},{"id":8,"slug":"cia-triad","title":"CIA Triad","content":"## \uD83D\uDD12 CIA Triad\\nThe CIA Triad represents the three core pillars of cybersecurity: **Confidentiality**, **Integrity**, and **Availability**.\\n\\n### Confidentiality\\nProtecting information from unauthorized access and disclosure.\\n- Encryption\\n- Access Controls\\n- Data Masking\\n- Physical Security\\n- Employee Training\\n\\n### Integrity\\nEnsuring data remains accurate, authentic, and unaltered unless modified intentionally by authorized users.\\n- Hashing\\n- Digital Signatures\\n- Checksums\\n- Access Controls\\n- Log Reviews & Audits\\n\\n### Availability\\nEnsuring systems, data, and resources remain accessible when needed.\\n- Redundancy (servers, data, network, power)\\n- Backups\\n- Load Balancing\\n- Disaster Recovery Planning\\n\\nThe CIA Triad forms the foundation of secure system design and risk management.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-01","created":"2025-08-01T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-01T10:00:00Z"},{"id":9,"slug":"security-controls","title":"Security Controls","content":"## \uD83D\uDEE1️ Security Controls\\nSecurity controls are measures used to protect systems and data by reducing risk and supporting the CIA Triad.\\n\\n### Categories\\n- **Technical Controls:** Firewalls, encryption, IDS/IPS, authentication.\\n- **Managerial Controls:** Policies, risk assessments, training, incident response planning.\\n- **Operational Controls:** Backups, account reviews, change management, user training.\\n- **Physical Controls:** Locks, guards, shredding, badges, cameras.\\n\\n### Control Types\\n- **Preventative:** Stop threats before they occur (e.g., MFA, firewalls).\\n- **Deterrent:** Discourage attackers (warning banners, lighting, cameras).\\n- **Detective:** Identify and alert on suspicious activity (IDS, logs).\\n- **Corrective:** Restore systems after an incident (patching, AV removal tools).\\n- **Compensating:** Alternatives when a primary control isn\'t feasible.\\n- **Directive:** Policies and guidelines defining acceptable behavior (AUP).\\n\\nSecurity controls form the foundation of protecting assets and reducing organizational risk.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-01","created":"2025-08-01T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-01T10:00:00Z"},{"id":10,"slug":"zero-trust-model","title":"Zero Trust Model","content":"## \uD83D\uDEE1️ Zero Trust Model\\nZero Trust is a security framework that assumes no user or device is trusted by default.\\n\\n### Core Principle\\n- **Trust nothing, verify everything**\\n\\n### Control Plane\\n- **Adaptive Identity:** Real-time verification based on user behavior, device, and location.\\n- **Threat Scope Reduction:** Limit access to only what\'s necessary, reducing attack surface.\\n- **Policy-Driven Access Control:** Role- and responsibility-based access management.\\n- **Secured Zones:** Isolated environments for sensitive data.\\n- **Policy Engine & Administrator:** Define, enforce, and manage access policies.\\n\\n### Data Plane\\n- **Subject/System:** User or device requesting access.\\n- **Policy Enforcement Point:** Gatekeeper enforcing access rules.\\n- **Implicit Trust Zones:** Areas with assumed safety, monitored carefully.\\n\\nZero Trust complements [[Security Controls]] and [[Risk Management]] by continuously validating users and devices to protect organizational assets.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-02","created":"2025-08-02T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-02T10:00:00Z"},{"id":11,"slug":"pki-encryption","title":"PKI & Encryption","content":"## \uD83D\uDD10 Cryptography & PKI\\n- **Cryptography:** Study of codes to protect information.\\n- **Public Key Infrastructure (PKI):** System managing asymmetric key pairs (public/private) for secure communication, authentication, and encrypted data transfer.\\n- **Public Key Cryptography:** Asymmetric encryption for encrypting and decrypting messages.\\n- **Symmetric Encryption:** Uses a single key (AES, DES, 3DES, Twofish, Blowfish, RC4/5/6).\\n- **Hybrid Encryption:** Asymmetric encryption used to transfer symmetric keys securely.\\n- **Stream & Block Ciphers:** Encrypt bit-by-bit or in fixed-size blocks.\\n- **Key Management Tools:** TPM, HSM, secure enclaves.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDEE1️ Data Protection Techniques\\n- **Tokenization:** Substitute sensitive data with non-sensitive tokens.\\n- **Data Masking:** Disguise sensitive data while keeping it usable.\\n- **Hashing:** One-way cryptographic function producing a fixed-length digest (MD5, SHA-1/2/3, RIPEMD, HMAC).\\n- **Salting & Key Stretching:** Strengthen passwords against cracking.\\n- **Pass the Hash & Birthday Attacks:** Common hash-based attacks.\\n\\n## ✍️ Digital Signatures\\n- Hash digest encrypted with sender\'s private key.\\n- Ensures integrity, authenticity, and non-repudiation.\\n- Used in code signing and Digital Security Standard (DSS).\\n\\n## ⛓️ Blockchain\\n- Immutable ledger tracking transactions.\\n- **Permissioned vs Public:** Controlled vs open ledgers.\\n- **Smart Contracts:** Self-executing, tamper-proof agreements.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCDC Certificates\\n- **Digital Certificates:** Bind public key to identity.\\n- **Certificate Authorities (CAs):** Issue and validate certificates.\\n- **Registration Authority (RA):** Collects info for certificates.\\n- **Types:** Wildcard, SAN, single-sided, dual-sided, self-signed, third-party.\\n- **Trust & Revocation:** Root of trust, CRLs, OCSP, OCSP Stapling.\\n- **Key Escrow & Recovery Agents:** Manage lost or secure keys.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-03","created":"2025-08-03T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-03T10:00:00Z"},{"id":12,"slug":"common-threat-actors","title":"Common Threat Actors","content":"## Threat Actors\\nAn individual or entity responsible for incidents impacting security and data protection.\\n\\n### Nation-state\\n- Government-sponsored attackers performing espionage, sabotage, or cyber warfare.\\n- Use advanced tools, zero-day exploits, custom malware.\\n- May conduct false flag attacks.\\n- Often called APTs (Advanced Persistent Threats).\\n\\n### Unskilled Attacker\\n- Individuals with limited technical expertise.\\n- Use pre-made scripts or tools (e.g., LOIC for DDoS attacks).\\n\\n### Hacktivist\\n- Driven by political, social, or environmental ideologies.\\n- Activities: website defacement, DDoS, doxing, data leaks.\\n- Notable groups: Anonymous, LulzSec.\\n\\n### Insider Threat\\n- Security risks originating from within the organization.\\n- Examples: data theft, sabotage, misuse of privileges.\\n\\n### Organized Crime\\n- Structured groups targeting financial gain.\\n- Techniques: ransomware, identity theft, credit card fraud.\\n- Often use cryptocurrencies, dark web, or cellular collection devices.\\n- Examples: FIN7, Carbanak.\\n\\n### Shadow IT\\n- Unapproved IT systems, devices, software, and services.\\n- Examples: personal devices for work, unapproved apps, cloud services, plugins/extensions.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-04","created":"2025-08-04T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-04T10:00:00Z"},{"id":13,"slug":"social-engineering","title":"Social Engineering","content":"## \uD83E\uDDE0 Human Vectors / Social Engineering\\nAttacks exploiting human psychology to gain unauthorized access or sensitive info.\\n\\n### Phishing \uD83D\uDCE7\\n- Spray and pray attacks using deceptive emails.\\n- **Spear Phishing:** Targeted users.\\n- **Whaling:** Targets high-profile executives (CEOs, CFOs).\\n- **Vishing:** Phone-based attacks.\\n- **Smishing:** Text message attacks.\\n\\n### Misinformation / Fraud \uD83D\uDCB0\\n- **Misinformation:** Unintentional false info.\\n- **Disinformation:** Intentional false info.\\n- **Identity Fraud:** Using someone else\'s info to deceive.\\n- **Invoice Scam:** Fake invoices to trick victims.\\n\\n### Impersonation \uD83D\uDD75️\\n- Assuming another’s identity to gain access.\\n- **Business Email Compromise:** Manipulating employees via internal emails.\\n- **Pretexting:** Fabricated scenario to extract info.\\n- **Brand Impersonation:** Pretending to represent a legit company.\\n- **Typosquatting:** Using domain names with typos to trick users.\\n\\n### Targeted Attacks \uD83C\uDFAF\\n- **Watering Hole:** Compromise websites your target uses.\\n- **Diversion Theft:** Distract to steal info.\\n- **Hoax:** Malicious deception via social media/email.\\n\\n### Physical / Observational Attacks \uD83D\uDC40\\n- **Shoulder Surfing:** Watching someone to gather info.\\n- **Dumpster Diving:** Searching trash for sensitive info.\\n- **Eavesdropping:** Secretly listening.\\n- **Baiting:** Leaving malware-infected devices (USBs) for victims to pick up.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-05","created":"2025-08-05T10:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-05T10:00:00Z"},{"id":14,"slug":"university-of-waterloo","title":"\uD83C\uDFEB University of Waterloo","content":"### \uD83C\uDF93 Bachelor of Computer Engineering\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCD8 1A Term\\n- COMMST 192 – Communication in the Engineering Profession\\n- ECE 105 – Classical Mechanics\\n- ECE 150 – Fundamentals of Programming\\n- ECE 190 – Engineering Profession and Practice\\n- ECE 198 – Project Studio\\n- MATH 115 – Linear Algebra for Engineering\\n- MATH 117 – Calculus I for Engineering\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCD7 1B Term\\n- ECE 106 – Electricity and Magnetism\\n- ECE 108 – Discrete Mathematics and Logic 1\\n- ECE 124 – Digital Circuits and Systems\\n- ECE 140 – Linear Circuits\\n- ECE 192 – Engineering Economics and Impact on Society\\n- MATH 119 – Calculus II for Engineering\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCD9 2A Term\\n- [[ECE 109 – Materials Chemistry for Engineers]]\\n- [[ECE 204 – Numerical Methods]]\\n- [[ECE 205 – Advanced Calculus 1 for Electrical and Computer Engineers]]\\n- [[ECE 222 – Digital Computers]]\\n- [[ECE 240 – Electronic Circuits 1]]\\n- [[ECE 250 – Algorithms and Data Structures]]\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDDE9 PD Courses\\n- PD 19 – Tactics for Workplace Success\\n- PD 20 – Strategies for Career Success\\n- PD 10 – Professional Responsibility in Computing\\n- PD 22 – Professionalism and Ethics in Engineering Practice\\n\\n## \uD83C\uDF31 Reflections from My Journey\\nBuild systems for yourself — good habits compound.\\nLearn how to learn. Spend real time thinking about how to understand things deeply and meaningfully.\\n\\nAlways ask yourself why you\'re doing something. What kind of life do I want to live after university?\\n\\nThere will be moments in university when you feel lonely. Don\'t stay in bed — step outside.\\n\\nEvery experience and every choice shapes who I am. Don’t be afraid — just try.\\n\\nWe live in a world of constant change, and we never know when it will shift. If I accept that anything in my life can change unexpectedly, then decisions become less scary. What matters most is having the confidence that whatever happens, I\'ll adapt and find my way again.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDE80 My Approach to Internships\\nThere\'s nothing more certain than actually trying something. Being inside an organization reveals sides of myself I didn\'t know existed. That\'s why I shouldn\'t assume beforehand what I will or won\'t enjoy.\\n\\n### \uD83C\uDFAF Reminder to myself\\nDon\'t waste energy debating whether a choice is right or wrong. **Make the choice right by the way you commit to it.**","tags":["University"],"date":"2023-09-01","created":"2023-09-01T00:00:00Z","updated":"2023-09-01T00:00:00Z"},{"id":15,"slug":"malware-types","title":"Malware Types","content":"### \uD83E\uDDA0 What is Malware?\\nMalware is any software intentionally designed to infiltrate, damage, or disrupt a system **without the user\'s knowledge**.\\n\\n- **Threat Vector:** The method used to break into a system.\\n- **Attack Vector:** The method used to break in *and infect* a system.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD10 Ransomware\\nEncrypts a victim’s data and demands payment for decryption.\\n\\n**Prevention:** Regular backups, software updates, MFA, user awareness training.\\n**Response:** Never pay ransom, isolate the system, notify authorities, restore from good backups.\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDDE8 Trojan\\nMalicious software disguised as legitimate applications.\\n- **RAT (Remote Access Trojan):** Gives attackers remote control over the victim’s machine.\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDEB1 Worm\\nStandalone malware that self-replicates without user interaction by exploiting vulnerabilities.\\n- Rapid replication can cause **DoS attacks**.\\n- Differs from viruses, which require user action.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDC41️ Spyware\\nSecretly monitors user activity and sends collected data to third parties.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCE6 Bloatware\\nUnnecessary pre-installed software consuming resources with little value.\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDDEC Viruses\\nMalicious code that attaches to clean files and spreads when executed.\\nTypes include:\\n- **Boot Sector Virus:** Loads during system boot.\\n- **Macro Virus:** Embedded in documents; executed when opened.\\n- **Program Virus:** Infects executable files.\\n- **Multipartite Virus:** Infects both boot sectors and programs.\\n- **Encrypted Virus:** Hides itself by encrypting its code.\\n- **Polymorphic Virus:** Alters its code on each run to evade detection.\\n- **Metamorphic Virus:** Rewrites itself entirely before infecting other files.\\n- **Stealth Virus:** Uses various techniques to avoid detection.\\n- **Armored Virus:** Adds protective layers to resist analysis.\\n- **Hoax:** Social engineering designed to scare users into harmful actions.\\n\\n## ⌨️ Keyloggers\\nRecord keystrokes to steal passwords or sensitive information.\\n- Can be **software-based** or **hardware-based**.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCA3 Logic Bomb\\nMalicious code triggered when specific conditions are met.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDEE0 Rootkits\\nTools that hide their presence and provide persistent administrative access.\\n- Often modify system files at the **kernel level (Ring 0)**.\\n**Techniques:**\\n- **DLL Injection:** Forcing another process to load malicious DLLs.\\n- **Shims:** Code placed between components to manipulate behavior.\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDDDF Zombies & Botnets\\n**Zombie:** A compromised computer remotely controlled by an attacker.\\n**Botnet:** A network of zombies used for:\\n- DDoS attacks\\n- Spam distribution\\n- Cryptocurrency mining\\n**C2 (Command & Control) Node:** Coordinates botnet activity.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD13 Backdoors\\nUnauthorized pathways allowing attackers to bypass normal authentication.\\n\\n**Easter Eggs:** Historically harmless jokes in code, but considered insecure.\\n\\n## ⚙️ Malware Exploitation Techniques\\nModern malware often uses **fileless techniques** to avoid signature detection.\\n\\n### ➤ **Fileless Malware**\\nRuns entirely in memory without writing malicious files to disk.\\n\\n### ➤ Stage 1: Dropper / Downloader\\n- **Dropper:** Launches the initial malware payload.\\n- **Downloader:** Fetches additional malware from remote servers.\\nTriggered when users click malicious links or open infected files.\\n\\n\\n### ➤ Stage 2: Shellcode & Additional Tools\\n- **Shellcode:** Lightweight code used to execute exploits.\\n- Often downloads RATs or implants for long-term access.\\n\\n### ➤ Actions and Objectives\\nThreat actors perform their primary goals:\\n- Data exfiltration\\n- File encryption\\n\\n### ➤ Concealment\\nTechniques to maintain stealth:\\n- Log deletion\\n- Hiding artifacts\\n- Obfuscation\\n\\n### ➤ \\"Living off the Land\\" (LOTL)\\nAttackers leverage legitimate system tools (e.g., PowerShell, WMI) to blend in and avoid detection.\\n","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-06","created":"2025-08-06T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-06T00:00:00Z"},{"id":16,"slug":"vulnerability-types","title":"Vulnerability Types","content":"## \uD83D\uDEE0️ Vulnerability Types\\nWeaknesses or flaws in hardware, software, configurations, or processes that attackers can exploit.\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDDE9 Application Vulnerabilities\\n**Memory Injection** – Malicious code inserted into memory (e.g., DLL injection).\\n**Buffer Overflow** – Data exceeds allocated memory and may overwrite return addresses.\\n**Race Conditions (TOC/TOU/TOE)** – Attackers exploit timing issues in processes. Prevent with locks/mutexes.\\n**Malicious Update** – Update process hijacked to deliver malware.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDDA5️ Operating System Vulnerabilities\\n**Unpatched Systems** – Missing security updates.\\n**Zero-day** – Unknown flaw with no available patch.\\n**Misconfiguration** – Weak or default system settings.\\n**Data Exfiltration** – Unauthorized transfer of sensitive data.\\n**Malicious Updates** – Compromised update channel poisoning trusted software.\\n\\n## \uD83C\uDF10 Web Vulnerabilities\\n**SQL Injection** – Injecting SQL commands (e.g., \' OR 1=1). Prevent with validation and sanitization.\\n**XML Injection / XXE** – Manipulating XML input to access local files or overload memory.\\n**XSS (Cross-Site Scripting)** – Injecting malicious scripts into trusted websites.\\n**CSRF/XSRF** – Trick users into unintended actions on authenticated sites.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD27 Hardware Vulnerabilities\\n**Firmware Flaws** – Weaknesses in device firmware.\\n**EOL / Legacy** – Unsupported or outdated hardware.\\n**Misconfiguration** – Poorly configured devices.\\nMitigation: hardening, patching, segmentation, decommissioning.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDDA5️ Virtualization Vulnerabilities\\n**VM Escape** – Breaking out of a VM to access the host.\\n**Resource Reuse** – Remnant data accessible between VMs.\\n\\n## ☁️ Cloud Vulnerabilities\\n**Misconfigured Buckets** – Public S3 or storage exposures.\\n**Weak IAM Roles** – Excessive or poorly managed permissions.\\n**Insecure APIs** – Unprotected or poorly validated endpoints.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDE9A Supply Chain Vulnerabilities\\n**Service Providers** – Weak remote access or shared infrastructure.\\n**Hardware Providers** – Backdoors, counterfeit parts.\\n**Software Providers** – Compromised updates or insecure dependencies.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD10 Cryptographic Vulnerabilities\\n**Weak Algorithms** – MD5, SHA-1.\\n**Stolen Keys** – Key exposure or reuse.\\n**Implementation Flaws** – Poor encryption setup.\\n\\n## ⚙️ Misconfiguration\\nDefault accounts, weak permissions, open ports, unencrypted services.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCF1 Mobile Vulnerabilities\\n**Side Loading** – Installing apps from untrusted sources.\\n**Jailbreaking** – Bypassing built-in security controls.\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD73️ Zero-Day\\n**Zero-day Vulnerability** – Unknown flaw.\\n**Zero-day Exploit** – Actively exploited before the vendor is aware.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-06","created":"2025-08-06T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-06T00:00:00Z"},{"id":17,"slug":"defense-in-depth","title":"Defense in Depth","content":"### \uD83D\uDEE1️ Defense in Depth\\n\\n**Defense in Depth** is a security strategy that uses **multiple layers of controls** to protect systems, data, and networks. Even if one layer fails, additional layers continue to provide protection.\\n\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Key Points:**\\n- Uses **stacked, overlapping security measures** rather than relying on a single control.\\n- Ensures **redundancy** so an attacker must bypass multiple barriers to succeed.\\n- Includes **technical, administrative, and physical controls**.\\n\\n**\uD83E\uDDE9 Examples of Layered Controls:**\\n- **Network layer:** firewalls, segmentation, VPNs\\n- **Host layer:** OS hardening, endpoint protection, patching\\n- **Application layer:** input validation, authentication, secure coding\\n- **Data layer:** encryption, access controls, monitoring\\n- **User layer:** security awareness training, MFA\\n\\n**\uD83C\uDFAF Goal:**\\nReduce the likelihood of compromise and **limit the impact** if a breach occurs.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-06","created":"2025-08-06T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-06T00:00:00Z"},{"id":18,"slug":"secure-network-segmentation","title":"Secure Network Segmentation","content":"### \uD83D\uDD17 Secure Network Segmentation\\n**Secure Network Segmentation** divides a network into **isolated segments** to reduce the attack surface and limit the impact of breaches.\\n\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Key Points:**\\n- **VLANs (Virtual LANs):** Logically separate network traffic within the same physical network to restrict access between departments or services.\\n- **DMZ (Demilitarized Zone):** Hosts public-facing services (e.g., web, email, DNS) and separates them from the internal network.\\n- **Purpose:** Limits lateral movement, enforces policy boundaries, and improves monitoring.\\n- **Best Practice:** Combine segmentation with **firewalls, access control lists (ACLs), and monitoring** for enhanced security.\\n\\n**\uD83C\uDFAF Goal:**\\nReduce exposure of sensitive internal resources and **contain potential attacks** within isolated network zones.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-07","created":"2025-08-07T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-07T00:00:00Z"},{"id":19,"slug":"data-protection","title":"Data Protection","content":"### \uD83D\uDD10 Data Protection\\n**Data Protection** involves implementing measures to secure sensitive information from unauthorized access or disclosure.\\n\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Key Methods:**\\n **Encryption:** Converts readable data (plaintext) into unreadable ciphertext using algorithms and keys. Protects data **at rest, in transit, and in use**. \\n- **Examples:** Full disk encryption, file encryption, database encryption, record-level encryption.\\n **Tokenization:** Replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive placeholders (tokens) while preserving usability.\\n- **Example:** Credit card numbers replaced with tokens for payment processing.\\n **Data Masking:** Conceals original data by replacing it with placeholder characters or values.\\n- **Example:** Showing only last 4 digits of a social security number.\\n **Other Measures:** Obfuscation, segmentation, and access/permission controls enhance data security.\\n\\n**\uD83C\uDFAF Goal:**\\nProtect sensitive information, **ensure compliance with regulations**, and reduce risk of data breaches.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-08","created":"2025-08-08T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-08T00:00:00Z"},{"id":20,"slug":"secure-baselines-hardening","title":"Secure Baselines & Hardening","content":"### \uD83D\uDEE1️ Secure Baselines & Hardening\\n**Secure Baselines** are standard security configurations applied to systems, networks, or applications to guarantee minimum security.\\n\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Establish:**\\nCreate a baseline by identifying required security controls and configurations.\\n- **Examples:** Defining password policies, disabling unnecessary services, enforcing encryption, setting logging requirements.\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Deploy:**\\n Apply secure baseline to systems, applications, or devices.\\n  - **Examples:** Firewalls, user permissions, encryption protocols, up-to-date antivirus.\\n  - **Automation Tools:** Group Policy (Windows), Ansible, SCCM, imaging.\\n  - **Cloud Example:** AWS Config for defining and deploying secure configurations across cloud resources.\\n\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Maintain:**\\n Continuously monitor and update baselines to address new vulnerabilities, patches, and organizational changes.\\n- **Examples:** Updating baseline after critical OS patches or new compliance requirements.\\n\\n**\uD83E\uDDE9 Hardening Targets:**\\n- **Mobile devices:** MDM, encryption, screen locks, remote wipe.\\n- **Workstations:** Disable unused ports/services, apply patches, enforce least privilege.\\n- **Switches:** Enable port security, disable unused ports, configure VLANs.\\n- **Routers:** Disable default accounts, secure management interfaces, ACLs.\\n- **Cloud Infrastructure:** Enforce IAM policies, restrict storage bucket access, logging.\\n- **Servers:** Patch OS, enforce access control, enable host-based firewalls.\\n- **ICS/SCADA:** Segregate networks, restrict external access, patch cautiously.\\n- **Embedded Systems / RTOS:** Lock firmware, restrict external ports, minimal code, isolate tasks.\\n- **IoT Devices:** Change default credentials, update firmware, segment networks.\\n\\n**\uD83C\uDFAF Goal:**\\nEnsure systems are configured securely, reduce vulnerabilities, and maintain consistent protection across all computing resources.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-09","created":"2025-08-09T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-09T00:00:00Z"},{"id":21,"slug":"vulnerability-management-lifecycle","title":"Vulnerability Management Lifecycle","content":"### \uD83D\uDD04 Vulnerability Management Lifecycle\\n**The Vulnerability Management Lifecycle** is a structured process used to identify, assess, remediate, and monitor vulnerabilities in systems, applications, and networks.\\n\\n**\uD83D\uDD11 Stages:**\\n\\n- **1. Identification:**\\n  - Systematically detect and categorize weaknesses.\\n  - **Methods:** Vulnerability scanning, threat intelligence feeds, penetration testing, static and dynamic code analysis.\\n  - **Tools/Examples:** Nessus, OpenVAS, OWASP ZAP, Burp Suite, Snyk, Dependabot.\\n\\n- **2. Analysis:**\\n  - Confirm vulnerabilities are real (reduce false positives/negatives).\\n  - Prioritize vulnerabilities based on severity, exploitability, and business impact.\\n  - **Standards:** CVSS scoring, CVE references, exposure factor calculation, environmental/contextual variables.\\n\\n- **3. Remediation:**\\n  - Implement actions to reduce risk.\\n  - **Techniques:** Patching, configuration changes, network segmentation, compensating controls.\\n  - Manage exceptions/exemptions with formal approvals if necessary.\\n\\n- **4. Validation:**\\n  - Verify that remediation actions were effective.\\n  - **Methods:** Rescanning, auditing, penetration testing, user verification.\\n\\n- **5. Reporting:**\\n  - Document and communicate findings and actions.\\n  - **Internal:** To IT/security teams and management.\\n  - **External:** To vendors, partners, or public (responsible disclosure, bug bounty programs).\\n\\n**\uD83C\uDFAF Goal:**\\nContinuously improve security posture by reducing vulnerabilities, ensuring compliance, and mitigating potential business impact.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-10","created":"2025-08-10T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-10T00:00:00Z"},{"id":22,"slug":"identity-access-management-iam","title":"Identity and Access Management (IAM)","content":"### \uD83D\uDD11 Identity and Access Management (IAM)\\nIAM ensures the right access for the right people at the right times.\\n\\n**1. Core Functions:**\\n- **Identification:** Claims a username or email as an identity.\\n- **Authentication:** Verifies the user’s identity, device, or system.\\n- **Authorization:** Establishes user access permissions or levels.\\n- **Accounting/Auditing:** Monitors and records user actions for compliance.\\n\\n**2. Account Lifecycle:**\\n- **Provisioning:** Create new user accounts, assign permissions, and provide access.\\n- **Deprovisioning:** Remove access rights when no longer required.\\n\\n**3. Permission Management:**\\n- **Principle of Least Privilege:** Users have only minimum access needed for their job.\\n- **User Account Control (UAC):** Ensures administrative actions are explicitly authorized.\\n- **Identity Proofing:** Verifying identity before account creation.\\n- **Federation:** Linking identities across multiple systems. (Steps: Login initiation → Redirection to IdP → Authentication → Assertion generation → Return to service provider → Verification and access.) \\n- **Single Sign-On (SSO):** One login to access multiple applications using a trusted IdP.\\n\\n**4. Directory Services:**\\n- **LDAP/LDAPS:** Stores user data, group memberships, roles, supports authentication.\\n- **OAuth:** Token-based authentication/authorization for third-party services.\\n- **SAML:** Standard for logging users into apps based on existing sessions.\\n\\n**5. Access Control Models:**\\n- **Mandatory (MAC):** Central authority determines access.\\n- **Discretionary (DAC):** Resource owner determines access.\\n- **Role-Based (RBAC):** Permissions granted based on user roles.\\n- **Rule-Based:** Access determined by admin-defined rules.\\n- **Attribute-Based (ABAC):** Access based on user, environment, and resource attributes.\\n- **Time-of-day Restrictions:** Controls access based on time.\\n- **Least Privilege:** Grant minimum access required.\\n- **Authorization Creep:** Excessive rights accumulated over time.\\n\\n**6. Multifactor Authentication (MFA):**\\n- Requires multiple independent authentication factors.\\n- **Factors:**\\n  - Something you know: password, PIN\\n  - Something you have: hardware/software token, smart card\\n  - Something you are: biometrics (fingerprint, face, iris)\\n  - Somewhere you are: location-based verification\\n  - Something you do: behavioral patterns (keystrokes, gestures)\\n- **Implementations:**\\n  - Biometrics: Pros - hard to fake; Cons - privacy concerns.\\n  - Hard/Soft tokens: Examples - key fobs, authenticator apps, SMS codes.\\n  - Security keys: FIDO2/U2F cryptographic authentication.\\n- **Authentication types:** Single-factor, two-factor, multifactor.\\n\\n**7. Password Concepts:**\\n- **Security Practices:** Length (12-16 chars), complexity, avoid reuse, periodic expiration.\\n- **Password Managers:** Store, generate, autofill, securely share passwords, cross-platform access.\\n- **Passwordless Options:** Biometric authentication, hardware tokens, OTPs, magic links, passkeys.\\n\\n**8. Privileged Access Management (PAM):**\\n- Restrict and monitor privileged access.\\n- **Techniques:**\\n  - Just-in-time permissions: Temporary admin access.\\n  - Password vaulting: Securely store/manage passwords.\\n  - Ephemeral credentials: Short-lived credentials reducing risk.\\n  - Temporal accounts: Time-limited access, auto-disabled/deleted.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-11","created":"2025-08-11T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-11T00:00:00Z"},{"id":23,"slug":"incident-response-process","title":"Incident Response Process","content":"### \uD83D\uDD11 Incident Response Process (NIST)\\n**Definition:**\\nAn incident is an act violating an explicit or implied security policy. The incident response process provides a structured approach to manage and mitigate security incidents effectively.\\n\\n**1. NIST Incident Response Phases:**\\n- **Preparation:** Strengthen systems and networks to resist attacks.\\n- **Detection:** Identify security incidents.\\n- **Analysis:** Thoroughly examine and evaluate the incident.\\n- **Containment:** Limit incident impact, secure data, protect operations.\\n- **Eradication:** Remove malicious activity after containment.\\n- **Recovery:** Restore systems and services to secure state.\\n- **Lessons Learned:** Document experiences and improve future response.\\n\\n**2. Reporting and Training:**\\n- **After-Action Report:** Collect formalized information about the incident.\\n- **Training:** Ensure staff understand processes, priorities, and past incident lessons.\\n- **Testing:** Practical exercises to simulate incidents.\\n  - Tabletop exercises: simulate incidents in a controlled environment.\\n  - Penetration tests: e.g., Metasploit, Cobalt Strike, Kali Linux, ParrotOS, Commando OS.\\n  - Simulation scenarios: phishing, ransomware, multi-stage attacks.\\n\\n**3. Root Cause Analysis:**\\n- Define/scope the incident.\\n- Determine causal relationships.\\n- Identify affected systems and elements.\\n- Implement effective solutions.\\n- Track solutions and improvements.\\n- Use a no-blame approach.\\n\\n**4. Threat Hunting:**\\n- Detect hidden threats not caught by regular monitoring.\\n- Establish hypothesis: predict likely high-impact events.\\n- Profile threat actors: insider, hacktivist, criminal, nation-state.\\n- Identify TTPs (tactics, techniques, procedures).\\n- Examine other hosts, create new IPS signatures.\\n- Integrate with threat intelligence.\\n\\n**5. Digital Forensics:**\\n- **Identification:** Secure scene and define evidence scope.\\n- **Collection:** Gather and preserve physical/digital evidence. (Follow order of volatility: memory → system state → storage → network logs → remote/archived data.)\\n- **Chain of Custody:** Document handling of evidence.\\n- **Disk Imaging:** Bit-by-bit copy of storage devices.\\n- **File Carving:** Extract files without relying on file system.\\n- **Analysis:** Scrutinize data for relevant info, timestamps, interactions.\\n- **Reporting:** Document findings, processes, methodologies.\\n\\n**6. Legal Considerations:**\\n- **Legal Hold:** Preserve all potentially relevant electronic data.\\n- **Acquisition:** Capture and hash system images, follow order of volatility. (Tools: FTK, EnCase.)\\n- **Preservation:** Backup copies, isolate critical systems, implement access controls.\\n- **E-discovery:** Identify, collect, and produce electronically stored info for legal proceedings.","tags":["Cybersecurity"],"date":"2025-08-12","created":"2025-08-12T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-08-12T00:00:00Z"},{"id":24,"slug":"ece109-materials-chemistry-for-engineers","title":"ECE 109 – Materials Chemistry for Engineers","content":"### \uD83D\uDCDA Concepts\\n\\n**Chapter 1:** INTRODUCTION & ATOMIC STRUCTURE AND BONDING\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n\\n**Chapter 2:** CRYSTALLINE STRUCTURE – PERFECTION\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n\\n**Chapter 3:** CRYSTAL DEFECTS AND NON-CRYSTALLINE STRUCTURE – IMPERFECTION\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n\\n**Chapter 4:** DIFFUSION\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n\\n**Chapter 5:** Diffusion\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n\\n**Chapter 6:** BAND THEORY AND ELECTRICAL PROPERTIES\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n\\n**Chapter 7:** OPTICAL & MAGNETIC PROPERTIES\\n- \\n- \\n- \\n","tags":["University"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":25,"slug":"ece-204-numerical-methods","title":"ECE 204 – Numerical Methods","content":"### \uD83D\uDCDA Concepts\\n\\n**Week 1**\\n- Representation of real numbers\\n\\n**Week 2**\\n- Tools for finding numerical algorithms\\n- Weighted averages\\n- Iteration and fixed-point iteration\\n- Linear algebra\\n\\n**Week 3**\\n- Interpolation\\n- Taylor series\\n- Bracketing\\n- Intermediate-value theorem\\n- Summary of tools and looking ahead\\n- Types and sources of error\\n\\n**Week 4**\\n- Introduction to approximating the value of expressions\\n- Evaluating a polynomial at a point and Horner\'s rule\\n- Using interpolating polynomials\\n- Approximating values using interpolating polynomials\\n- Approximating derivatives using interpolating polynomials\\n\\n**Week 5**\\n- Approximating integrals using interpolating polynomials\\n- Least-squares best-fitting polynomials\\n- Approximating a point using least-squares best-fitting polynomials\\n- Approximating the derivative using least-squares best-fitting polynomials\\n- Approximating an integral using least-squares best-fitting polynomials\\n\\n**Week 6**\\n- Approximating solutions to algebraic equations\\n- Approximating the solution to the quadratic equation\\n- Approximating solutions to non-linear algebraic equations\\n- Newton\'s method\\n- The bisection method\\n- The bracketed secant method\\n- The secant method\\n- Muller\'s method\\n- Inverse quadratic interpolation\\n- Approximating solutions to systems of linear equations\\n- The Gauss-Seidel method\\n- The method of successive over-relaxation\\n\\n**Week 7**\\n- Approximating solutions to systems of non-linear equations\\n- Newton\'s method in n dimensions\\n- Approximating solutions to analytic equations\\n- Approximating solutions to ordinary differential equations (ODEs)\\n- Approximating solutions to initial-value problems (IVPs)\\n- Approximating solutions to first-order IVPs\\n- Euler\'s method\\n\\n**Week 8**\\n- Heun\'s method\\n- The 4th-order Runge-Kutta method\\n- Error analysis of these methods\\n- Adaptive techniques for 1st-order initial-value problems (IVPs)\\n- Adaptive Euler-Heun method\\n- Adaptive Dormand-Prince method\\n\\n**Week 9**\\n- Approximating solutions to systems of 1st-order IVPs\\n- Approximating solutions to higher-order IVPs\\n- Approximating solutions to systems of higher-order IVPs\\n- Approximating solutions to boundary-value problems\\n- The shooting method\\n\\n**Week 10**\\n- The finite-difference method\\n- Neumann and insulated boundary conditions\\n- Approximating solutions to partial differential equations\\n- The heat equation in one dimension\\n\\n**Week 11**\\n- The wave equation in one dimension\\n- Laplace\'s equation\\n- Optimization\\n- Optimizing functions of a real variable\\n- Step-by-step optimization\\n- Newton\'s method for finding extrema\\n\\n**Week 12**\\n- The golden-ratio search\\n- Successive parabolic interpolation\\n- Optimizing functions of a vector variable\\n- Hooke-Jeeves method\\n- Newton\'s method for finding extrema in n dimensions\\n- Gradient descent\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD17 Backlinks\\n\\n**Related Topics:**\\n- [[MATLAB]]\\n- [[Linear Algebra]]\\n- [[Interpolation]]\\n- [[Root Finding]]\\n- [[Newton\'s Method]]\\n- [[Differential Equations]]\\n- [[Runge-Kutta Methods]]\\n- [[Optimization]]\\n- [[Partial Differential Equations]]\\n- [[Finite Difference Method]]","tags":["University"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":26,"slug":"ece-205-advanced-calculus-1","title":"ECE 205 – Advanced Calculus 1 for Electrical and Computer Engineers","content":"### \uD83D\uDCDA Concepts\\n\\n[[First Order Differential Equations]]\\n\\n[[Second Order Differential Equations]]\\n\\n[[Laplace Transforms]]\\n\\n[[Fourier Series]]\\n\\n[[Linear First and Second Order Partial Differential Equations with Constant Coefficients]]","tags":["University"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":27,"slug":"ece-222-digital-computers","title":"ECE 222 – Digital Computers","content":"### \uD83D\uDCDA Concepts\\n\\n- Number systems review\\n- RISC-V instruction set, addressing modes, subroutine linkage\\n- Assembly language translation, linking, loading\\n- Memory-mapped I/O, polling, interrupts, DMA\\n- Processor design: datapath, control unit\\n- Pipelining: hazards, stalling, data forwarding, performance\\n- Memory technology: SRAM, DRAM, DIMM\\n- Memory hierarchy: caches, secondary storage, virtual memory\\n- Computer arithmetic\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD17 Backlinks\\n\\n**Related Topics:**\\n- [[Computer Architecture]]\\n- [[RISC-V Architecture]]\\n- [[Assembly Programming]]\\n- [[Processor Design]]\\n- [[Memory Hierarchy]]\\n- [[Cache Memory]]\\n- [[Virtual Memory]]\\n- [[Pipelining]]\\n- [[Computer Arithmetic]]\\n- [[Input-Output Systems]]","tags":["University"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":28,"slug":"ece-240-electric-circuits-2","title":"ECE 240 – Electronic Circuits 1","content":"### \uD83D\uDCDA Concepts\\n\\n**Week 1: Circuit Analysis Review & Frequency Response**\\n- Review of ECE 140: Basic circuit laws, nodal analysis, circuit theorems\\n- Phasor analysis review\\n- Frequency response and Bode plots\\n- Complex numbers review\\n\\n**Weeks 2 & 3: Operational Amplifiers**\\n- Ideal op amp characteristics and circuits\\n- Non-ideal op amp behavior: limits, offsets, bias currents\\n- Finite gain, bandwidth, and slew rate\\n- Active filters with op amps\\n\\n**Weeks 4 & 5: Diodes**\\n- Ideal diode model and characteristics\\n- Diode structure and exponential model\\n- Small-signal diode models and applications\\n- Rectifiers and filter capacitors\\n\\n**Weeks 6 & 8: Step Response**\\n- Natural response of RC and RL circuits\\n- First-order step response\\n- Second-order RLC circuits: natural and step response\\n- Series and parallel RLC configurations\\n\\n**Weeks 9-12: MOSFETs and CMOS**\\n- MOSFET operation and DC analysis\\n- Small-signal models for MOSFET amplifiers\\n- Amplifier configurations and biasing\\n- CMOS logic gates and voltage transfer characteristics\\n- Propagation delay, gate sizing, and power dissipation\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDCD6 Textbook References\\n- **EC**: Fundamentals of Electric Circuits, 7th Ed.\\n- **MC**: Microelectronic Circuits, 8th Ed.\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD17 Backlinks\\n\\n**Related Topics:**\\n- [[Circuit Analysis]]\\n- [[Operational Amplifiers]]\\n- [[Diodes]]\\n- [[Transient Response]]\\n- [[Frequency Response]]\\n- [[Bode Plots]]\\n- [[MOSFETs]]\\n- [[CMOS Logic]]\\n- [[Amplifiers]]\\n- [[Filters]]","tags":["University"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":29,"slug":"ece-250-data-structures-and-algorithms","title":"ECE 250 – Algorithms and Data Structures","content":"### \uD83D\uDCDA Concepts\\n\\n**I. Foundational Concepts & Analysis**\\n- Algorithm basics and systematic development\\n- Complexity analysis and Big-O notation\\n- C++ programming fundamentals\\n- Linux environment and command line tools\\n\\n**II. Abstract Data Types (ADTs) and Linear Data Structures**\\n- Abstraction principles and ADT implementation\\n- Queues (FIFO), Stacks (LIFO), Sets, and Maps\\n- Linked Lists: singly, doubly, and circular variations\\n- Efficiency tradeoffs in basic operations\\n\\n**III. Hierarchical Data Structures (Trees)**\\n- Tree terminology and traversal methods\\n- Binary Search Trees (BSTs) and operations\\n- Self-balancing trees: AVL and Red-Black Trees\\n- Heaps, Priority Queues, and their operations\\n\\n**IV. Associative Structures (Hash Tables)**\\n- Hash table fundamentals and collision handling\\n- Hash functions and load factor management\\n- Collision resolution: external chaining and probing\\n\\n**V. Sorting Algorithms**\\n- O(N\xb2) algorithms: Bubble, Selection, Insertion Sort\\n- O(NlogN) algorithms: Merge, Quick, Heap Sort\\n- Non-comparison sorting: Radix Sort\\n- Sorting properties: stability and adaptivity\\n\\n**VI. Graph Theory and Algorithms**\\n- Graph ADT and implementations (adjacency matrix/list)\\n- Graph search: DFS and BFS\\n- Shortest path algorithms: Dijkstra\'s\\n- Minimum Spanning Tree: Prim\'s and Kruskal\'s\\n\\n**VII. Algorithm Design Paradigms**\\n- Brute Force and Greedy Algorithms\\n- Divide and Conquer approach\\n- Dynamic Programming and memoization\\n\\n### \uD83D\uDD17 Backlinks\\n\\n**Related Topics:**\\n- [[Data Structures]]\\n- [[Algorithms]]\\n- [[Complexity Analysis]]\\n- [[Big-O Notation]]\\n- [[Trees]]\\n- [[Graphs]]\\n- [[Sorting Algorithms]]\\n- [[Hash Tables]]\\n- [[C++ Programming]]\\n- [[Algorithm Design]]\\n- [[Binary Search Trees]]\\n- [[AVL Trees]]\\n- [[Red-Black Trees]]\\n- [[Priority Queues]]\\n- [[Graph Algorithms]]\\n- [[Dynamic Programming]]\\n- [[Greedy Algorithms]]","tags":["University"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":30,"slug":"google-cybersecurity-certificate","title":"Google Cybersecurity Certification","content":"### \uD83D\uDEE1️ Google Cybersecurity Professional Certificate\\n#### ⏳ Study Duration: 2 months\\n#### \uD83D\uDCC4 Certificate & Notes\\n[View Google Cybersecurity Certificate](/pdf/Coursera A7NWW0T7DQPF.pdf)\\n[Download Course Notes PDF](/pdf/Google Cybersecurity Certificate.pdf)","tags":["Cybersecurity","Certification"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":31,"slug":"matlab","title":"MATLAB","content":"#### \uD83D\uDCC4 Certificate & Notes\\n[View MATLAB Coursera Certificate](/pdf/Coursera AHWBQDU0ZEOJ.pdf)\\n[Access my MATLAB Notes on Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1eNK1IX1xOWIT3ZxvrGpV_qlsPseP-opV?usp=sharing)\\n\\nI used MATLAB to complete projects in ECE 204.","tags":["Programming","Certification"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":32,"slug":"docker-kubernetes","title":"Docker & Kubernetes","content":"#### \uD83D\uDCC4 Certificate & Notes\\n[View Docker & Kubernetes Udemy Certificate](/pdf/docker-kubernetes.pdf)\\n[Access my Docker & Kubernetes Notes on Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/14kRmygfedQRnE5gS9qDiqs54Tr3vc0mF?usp=drive_link)\\n\\nI used Docker and Kubernetes to understand containerization, orchestration, and modern cloud-native workflows. This certification helped me build foundational skills that I now apply when learning cloud infrastructure (AWS/GCP) and deploying applications in my personal projects.","tags":["Programming","Certification"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":33,"slug":"computer-vision-image-processing","title":"Computer Vision & Image Processing","content":"#### \uD83D\uDCC4 Certificate & Notes\\n[View IBM Computer Vision Coursera Certificate](/pdf/Coursera V3VPXOHXT9JG.pdf)\\n[Access my Computer Vision & Image Processing Notes on Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/15tjKeP3mPkLtQgxz4qwLaMFX-AQeWNHF)\\n\\nI studied Computer Vision because I was interested in how machines interpret images, and I also wanted to build a handwriting recognition project from scratch. This course gave me the foundational skills to understand modern image processing and deep learning–based vision systems.\\n\\n### \uD83E\uDDE0 What I Learned\\nThrough this course, I gained a full end-to-end understanding of how computer vision systems are built — from raw image processing to deep learning–based classification.\\n\\n#### \uD83D\uDCF7 Core Computer Vision Concepts\\n- How digital images work (pixels, color channels, grayscale, intensity mapping)\\n- Image preprocessing and transformation using **PIL** and **OpenCV**\\n- Feature extraction techniques such as **Histogram of Oriented Gradients (HOG)**\\n- Implementing traditional machine learning models for vision tasks: KNN, SVM, Logistic Regression, Neural Networks\\n\\n#### \uD83E\uDD16 Deep Learning & Advanced Techniques\\n- Building and training convolutional neural networks (CNNs)\\n- Data augmentation to improve model performance\\n- Transfer learning for faster training and higher accuracy\\n- Object detection methods including Haar cascades\\n\\n#### \uD83D\uDEE0️ Practical Applications Completed\\n- Handwritten digit recognition\\n- Simple object classification (cats vs. dogs)\\n- Metal structure detection\\n- Rust identification using image features\\n- Car detection using Haar cascade classifiers\\n\\n","tags":["Programming","Certification"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"},{"id":34,"slug":"ros2","title":"ROS2 (Robot Operating System 2)","content":"These are my structured notes from my Udemy ROS2 courses, covering fundamental robotics concepts and development workflows in ROS2 (Humble). \\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCC4 Notes & Certificates\\n [Access my ROS2 Notes & Certification on Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1xVsT3GeWodxFJxiNf6CyM_KYrkvdIjQZ?usp=drive_link)\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDCD8 Course Overview\\nI learned to create, build, and use fundamental ROS2 components:\\n- **Nodes** – Core executable units in ROS2\\n- **Topics** – Asynchronous communication between nodes\\n- **Services** – Synchronous request-response communication\\n- **Custom Messages** – Defining custom message types\\n- **Parameters** – Node configuration at runtime\\n- **Launch Files** – Running multiple nodes together\\n- **ROS2 Tools** – Command-line utilities for debugging\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDD27 Core ROS2 Concepts\\n### **Nodes**\\n- Independent subprograms performing specific tasks\\n- Communicate through topics, services, and parameters\\n- Can be written in Python or C++\\n\\n**Python Template:**\\n```python\\nclass MyNode(Node):\\n    def __init__(self):\\n        super().__init__(\\"node_name\\")\\n        # Node initialization\\n\\ndef main():\\n    rclpy.init()\\n    node = MyNode()\\n    rclpy.spin(node)\\n    rclpy.shutdown()\\n```\\n\\n**C++ Template:**\\n```cpp\\nclass MyNode : public rclcpp::Node {\\npublic:\\n    MyNode() : Node(\\"node_name\\") {\\n        // Node initialization\\n    }\\n};\\n\\nint main(int argc, char **argv) {\\n    rclcpp::init(argc, argv);\\n    auto node = std::make_shared<MyNode>();\\n    rclcpp::spin(node);\\n    rclcpp::shutdown();\\n    return 0;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### **Topics**\\n- Asynchronous message-passing system\\n- Publishers send messages\\n- Subscribers receive them\\n- Nodes do not need direct knowledge of one another\\n\\n### **Services**\\n- Synchronous client–server communication\\n- Clients send requests; servers send back responses\\n- Ideal when a response is required\\n\\n### **Custom Interfaces**\\n- Creating custom **.msg** and **.srv** types\\n- Defining dedicated interface packages\\n- Configuring CMakeLists.txt and package.xml for builds\\n\\n### **Parameters**\\n- Node configuration at runtime\\n- Must be declared before use\\n- Can be set via command line or launch files\\n\\n### **Launch Files**\\n- Start multiple nodes together\\n- Support **XML** and **Python** formats\\n- Essential for complex systems and simulations\\n\\n## \uD83D\uDEE0️ Key ROS2 Tools & Commands\\n- `ros2 run` – Run executables\\n- `ros2 node list/info` – Inspect nodes\\n- `ros2 topic list/echo/info` – Debug topics\\n- `ros2 service list/call` – Service tools\\n- `ros2 interface show` – Inspect message/service types\\n- `ros2 param list/get/set` – Parameter tools\\n- `ros2 bag record/play` – Record/playback data\\n- `rqt_graph` – Visualize node communication\\n- `rqt` – GUI tool suite\\n\\n## \uD83E\uDDEA Development Workflow\\n1. Create workspace: `mkdir -p ros2_ws/src`\\n2. Create packages: `ros2 pkg create`\\n3. Write nodes using Python/C++ templates\\n4. Add dependencies to **package.xml** and **CMakeLists.txt**\\n5. Build: `colcon build`\\n6. Source environment: `source install/setup.bash`\\n7. Run and debug your nodes","tags":["Robotics","Certification"],"date":"2025-11-24","created":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z","updated":"2025-11-24T00:00:00Z"}]}')}}]);